snippet.textDisplay: I love this interview SO much and am so grateful for her bringing her dignity, divinity and grace to the wider audience and owning her truth. Having insight, acceptance for the deck we've been dealt is the best thing we can do for ourselves. and those who are trying to support us. It can be very difficult to allow ourselves to be vulnerable and trust those who are there for us personally and professionally with this diagnosis. What an opportunity for Saved By The Bell to highlight the very real experience of the onset of this diagnosis as young adults with a reunion. What a gift to the millions of people who are shunned/stigmatized by society, their families, and themselves if Lark Voorhies gets to add her story to the Saved By The Bell franchise... if Lisa Marie Turtle comes out and is embraced by her friends when she shares her experiences and treatment...the fear, the support and the triumph. For more info/and to support overcoming stigma of mental illness search/suppport NAMI.org.

snippet.textDisplay: Why are all the comments bad mouthing her former cast mates ? She was going through some very dark times and she wasn’t all there when it came to her mental health. I don’t see how people she worked with 30 years ago have anything to do with her life now. Would it be good to see her as part of a Saved by the Bell reunion? Sure. But we all do not have any idea how she treated her cast mates after the show was over. We only have her side of the story. I have a feeling that there is way more to this than they not calling her up, or inviting her to a dinner. Sometimes, even though you have a mental illness, people get to a point where they cannot keep trying to bend over backwards in order to appease you. People get tired, it’s just life. I wonder how many coworkers from 1990 we all keep in touch with. I’m sure it’s not many.

snippet.textDisplay:
I know about mental illness in the struggles that brings firsthand and I don't say that out of looking for pity from anyone else nor out of self-pity but I totally understand what she's dealing with on top depression its such a battle DAILY and how hard it is especially as a woman of color (myself included) to actually announced it because people of color have been taught on how desensitize themselves not on purpose but through trauma it's just something we felt like we had to do throughout the generations to survive to make it to just be too just to live you know you don't speak about it you don't say don't put no one in your business but I got to say she is handling herself so well that blonde is looking great on her I mean she just looks so snatched and lovely and just the glow that's in her face well-spoken just awesome and she looks like she's trying you can see that there's still some residual damage but she is fighting with the help of her therapist and her mom and even for the lack of support that she may face from her fellow castmates she's definitely getting it from who she needs it the most and that's a blessing family a lot of times will turn their backs on you quicker than people you work with/friends/strangers hopefully her fellow castmates can get it together more power to Lisa I wish the best for her

Also shot out to Keke Palmer and Taraji P Henson who have also spoken about this previously in the last couple of years and they're about and how they deal with mental illness and what it means in the black community and what should be done and also on a bravery for admitting it and not ignoring it

snippet.textDisplay: It kinda hurts me to see Lark Voorhies suffering like this...Lisa Turtle is a character I grew up with! Fashionable, confident, beautiful, she was one of those generation x pop culture stars I looked up to. She seems like a VERY sweet person and frankly, doesn't deserve to be shut out of the group like that...why couldn't they have found some way, ANY way, to include her? I mean, damn. She was a huge part of Saved by the Bell's success, in my opinion. Lark was there from the very start with Good Morning Miss Bliss (also remember that one). They could've done better here, because despite what the reasons may be, it looks cold and insensitive.
